  "prompt": "My pet cat scratched me accidentally.Its not vaccinated and I'm from India. 7 days have passed but the cat is fully well. Do I need anti-rabies shots?",
  "response": "In India, rabies is a serious concern, and post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) for rabies is often recommended in cases of potential exposure, especially from unvaccinated animals. Here's what you should consider:\n\n1. **Current Status of the Cat**:\n   - Since your cat is healthy and showing no signs of rabies (such as aggression, excessive salivation, or neurological symptoms) after 7 days, the risk of rabies transmission is significantly reduced. Rabies in animals typically leads to death within 10 days of showing symptoms.\n\n2. **World Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines**:\n   - According to WHO, if the animal remains healthy for 10 days after the exposure, PEP is not necessary. Since 7 days have already passed and your cat is well, you\u2019re close to this threshold.\n\n3. **Indian Context**:\n   - In India, where rabies is endemic, healthcare providers often err on the side of caution. If the cat has not been vaccinated for rabies, you may still be advised to start PEP as a precautionary measure.\n\n4. **What You Should Do**:\n   - Consult a healthcare professional immediately, preferably at a government hospital or rabies clinic, to assess your risk and get personalized advice.\n   - If they recommend PEP, it\u2019s better to start it as soon as possible, as rabies is almost always fatal once symptoms appear.\n\n5. **Preventive Measures**:\n   - In the future, ensure your cat is vaccinated against rabies to reduce any risk of exposure.\n   - Practice good wound care by thoroughly washing the scratch with soap and water for at least 15 minutes and applying an antiseptic.\n\nWhile the risk may be low in your case, it\u2019s always safer to seek medical advice promptly, given the serious consequences of rabies.",
